  "course_description": "Examines interactions between economic developments (domestic and external) and political changes (domestic and external). Begins with general views and then examines particular issues (e.g., trade, monetary, development, environmental).",
  "course_notes": "In this course, students will learn to describe and interpret economic outcomes and government policy choices affecting international trade, international investment and supply chains, and global capital flows, exchange rates, and interest rates. Students will be able to define, apply, and critically evaluate a core set of concepts and arguments used to interpret, explain, and analyze the outcomes of these phenomena. And students will deploy that knowledge to analyze and generate policy evaluations of key contemporary cases shaping the global economy today and in the future.",
